Here is an example of Rust code that reads a CSV file and prints a table with the name, address, and phone number of each person:

``` 
use std::io::{Read, Write};
use std::fs::File;
use std::path::Path;

fn main() {
    let mut file = File::open("person.csv")?;
    let mut reader = Read::from(file.read_line().unwrap());
    let mut writer = Write::new();

    while reader.is_valid() {
        let mut row = reader.next();
        let (name, address, phone) = match row {
            (Some(name), Some(address), Some(phone)) => (name, address, phone),
            _ => ("", "", ""),
        };

        writer.write(name.unwrap())?;
        writer.write(address.unwrap())?;
        writer.write(phone.unwrap())?;
    }

    writer.close()?;
    file.close()?;
}
```

This code opens the `person.csv` file and reads it line by line. It then stores the name, address, and phone number of each person in three separate variables, `name`, `address`, and `phone`, and continues to read the file until it has all been read. It then writes the names, addresses, and phone numbers to a new file and closes the original file and the reader.

Note that this code assumes that the `person.csv` file has the following format:

``` 
name, address, phone
John, New York, 123 Main St.
Mary, Los Angeles, 456-7890
```

You will need to adjust the code to match your own CSV file format.

